WEBVTT

00:35.118 --> 00:37.370
This land is your land

00:39.998 --> 00:42.751
This land is my land

00:45.754 --> 00:48.256
From California

00:49.215 --> 00:53.386
To the New York island

00:54.637 --> 00:58.266
From the redwood forest

00:59.768 --> 01:03.938
To the Gulf Stream waters

01:04.773 --> 01:06.399
I tell you

01:06.441 --> 01:08.902
This land

01:08.943 --> 01:12.697
Was made for you and me

01:12.739 --> 01:13.907
Yeah

01:19.454 --> 01:24.000
One bright sunny morning

01:24.042 --> 01:28.421
In the shadow of a steeple

01:28.463 --> 01:33.259
Down by the welfare office

01:33.301 --> 01:38.348
I saw my people

01:38.389 --> 01:40.767
I was wondering

01:40.809 --> 01:43.269
If this land

01:43.311 --> 01:48.149
Was made for you and me

02:21.683 --> 02:23.434
I was so nervous.

02:28.523 --> 02:31.109
I needn't have
         been scared at all.

02:59.721 --> 03:01.848
--Oh, children.

03:01.890 --> 03:05.351
Does this sound desperate, Lucy?

03:07.228 --> 03:10.398
"Despite the many
     claims on your generosity,

03:10.440 --> 03:13.902
I cannot think of any cause
             more urgent

03:13.943 --> 03:16.696
than the care
 and well-being of our soldiers."

03:16.738 --> 03:19.532
No, I think that strikes
        just the right note.

03:19.574 --> 03:21.034
Oh, good.
       I can't tell sometimes.

03:21.075 --> 03:22.535
Hickory, dickory, dock.

03:22.577 --> 03:25.121
The mouse
          ran up the clock!

03:25.163 --> 03:26.789
I'll need you to draw up a list

03:26.831 --> 03:28.625
of the wealthiest patrons
              in town.

03:28.666 --> 03:30.293
Oh, I have the list right here.

03:30.335 --> 03:33.004
-The clock struck one.
          -Ooh, very good.

03:33.046 --> 03:37.175
Oh, Elliot, leave Lucy alone.
           We're working.

03:37.217 --> 03:38.426
The mouse ran down.

03:38.468 --> 03:40.178
Hickory, dickory, dock!

03:40.220 --> 03:42.055
Oh, I also need the--

03:42.096 --> 03:45.808
Oh, yes. Uh, your speech
         for the Red Cross.

03:45.850 --> 03:49.062
I don't know what I'd do
         without you, Lucy.

03:51.105 --> 03:53.650
I made two small edits.

03:53.691 --> 03:56.027
Um, Eleanor. Eleanor,

03:56.069 --> 03:59.030
Secretary Daniels and his wife
     will be in town on Friday.

03:59.072 --> 04:00.907
I mean, this
     could be good for Franklin

04:00.949 --> 04:02.533
if you have them over for lunch.

04:02.575 --> 04:04.494
At lunch, she's touring
         the navy hospital.

04:04.535 --> 04:06.704
-Are we free for dinner?
     -Yes, I believe so.

04:06.746 --> 04:09.374
Dinner, then.

04:09.415 --> 04:11.918
Oh, Louis,
     that cough sounds terrible.

04:11.960 --> 04:15.255
-It's fine.
    -Daddy's home!

04:15.296 --> 04:19.217
There you are! There you are,
      my little cubs. 

04:19.259 --> 04:22.303
I missed you too. Take my hand.

04:22.345 --> 04:25.473
Elliot, every time
      I turn my back, you grow.

04:25.515 --> 04:28.685
-How is that possible?
    -Leave your father some room.

04:28.726 --> 04:30.270
You'll topple him over.

04:30.311 --> 04:33.106
-And I missed you.
              -Me too.

04:33.147 --> 04:34.857
I'll be on my way,
              Eleanor.

04:34.899 --> 04:36.567
Thank you, Lucy.

04:36.609 --> 04:39.529
John! 

04:39.570 --> 04:40.947
Welcome home, Mr. Roosevelt.

04:41.739 --> 04:43.116
Ms. Mercer.

04:46.327 --> 04:49.622
John. 
        Children, follow me.

04:49.664 --> 04:51.541
He wants us here so bad.

05:28.119 --> 05:29.329
Hmm.

06:02.570 --> 06:06.157
"Dear Franklin,
 as I lay in bed, awake at night,

06:06.199 --> 06:08.785
I wonder if you
           are thinking of me.

06:08.826 --> 06:11.412
I see the stars
           outside my window,

06:14.916 --> 06:18.503
and in them trace our names
             with my finger.

06:18.544 --> 06:20.630
They harmonize well together.

06:30.056 --> 06:33.851
I love you, your dearest Lucy."

06:44.737 --> 06:46.322
"Every day of missing you

06:46.364 --> 06:49.242
convinces me
         that our love is true."

06:59.627 --> 07:02.964
"I dream of starting
         our new life together."

07:09.137 --> 07:10.513
Eleanor?

07:10.555 --> 07:12.807
-What's the matter?

07:20.398 --> 07:21.774
Lucy!

07:24.277 --> 07:26.279
My Lucy?

07:28.406 --> 07:31.033
Of all the women in the world,
          you sleep with--

07:31.075 --> 07:33.661
Why would you
         sleep with my Lucy?

07:33.703 --> 07:36.664
-Let me explain.
 -I thought a man was supposed to

07:36.706 --> 07:40.126
sleep with his own secretary,
        not with his wife's!

07:40.168 --> 07:42.462
It was a mistake. A-A fantasy.

07:42.503 --> 07:44.589
I thought what
         we had was special.

07:44.630 --> 07:45.798
It is.

07:45.840 --> 07:46.966
Well, then why?

07:50.386 --> 07:51.596
I-I-- 

07:51.637 --> 07:53.222
I don't know. I--

07:53.264 --> 07:55.558
I-I felt lonely.

07:55.600 --> 07:56.809
No.

07:59.270 --> 08:00.813
Lonely?

08:01.731 --> 08:02.940
But...

08:04.317 --> 08:06.903
I thought we had
         a future together!

08:06.944 --> 08:11.282
But you two have been
       plotting and planning!

08:11.324 --> 08:12.533
Why?

08:14.368 --> 08:15.995
I'm so sorry, Eleanor. I--

08:16.037 --> 08:19.832
While I was pregnant
            and nursing.

08:19.874 --> 08:23.586
And bearing your children!

08:23.628 --> 08:28.174
All you could think of was
   running away with Lucy Mercer!

08:35.264 --> 08:36.641
Who else knows?

08:36.682 --> 08:38.059
What does it matter?

08:38.100 --> 08:41.812
Who else knows, Franklin?
             Who knows?

08:42.813 --> 08:45.316
Louis, Steve Early, Mother.

08:45.358 --> 08:46.692
Louis.

08:47.401 --> 08:50.905
Louis! And your mother!

09:16.597 --> 09:18.349
There's never been
              a divorce

09:18.391 --> 09:20.643
in the Roosevelt family.

09:22.728 --> 09:25.356
And that's not going
           to change now.

09:25.398 --> 09:27.858
It had been going on for years.

09:28.859 --> 09:30.486
Everyone knew.

09:31.612 --> 09:32.780
You knew.

09:32.822 --> 09:36.784
Eleanor. When you marry a man,

09:36.826 --> 09:40.037
you can't be surprised
             when he...

09:40.079 --> 09:42.123
acts like a man.

09:42.164 --> 09:44.500
And, when you marry
          a capable woman,

09:44.542 --> 09:48.087
you can't be surprised
     when she acts like herself.

09:50.423 --> 09:52.842
It's no use, Mother.

09:52.883 --> 09:55.553
Eleanor has made her decision.

09:55.595 --> 09:56.637
Hmm.

09:58.931 --> 10:01.642
If you file for divorce,

10:01.684 --> 10:04.854
I will cut you both off
           without a cent.

10:04.895 --> 10:09.442
No house,
    not your rooms here. Nothing.

10:11.902 --> 10:14.572
Now, you will stay married.

10:16.449 --> 10:18.618
And I will even, um...

10:19.952 --> 10:22.038
not only support you,

10:22.997 --> 10:25.249
but pay an additional allowance

10:25.291 --> 10:27.126
for the pain
       that you are suffering.

10:28.919 --> 10:33.633
I would rather earn my own money
        and keep my dignity.

10:33.674 --> 10:36.093
If you get a divorce,
        you will do neither.

10:36.135 --> 10:39.597
The scandal will be too great
            to overcome.

10:39.639 --> 10:41.307
For both of you.

10:43.017 --> 10:46.228
I know that I'm experiencing

10:46.270 --> 10:48.981
a disappointment
    like I've never felt before.

10:52.735 --> 10:54.987
But I'm sure
   that it can't possibly compare

10:55.029 --> 10:58.157
to the pain
      that you're experiencing.

10:58.199 --> 10:59.909
You have my sympathy, darling.

11:02.036 --> 11:03.287
However...

11:07.500 --> 11:09.168
you will stay married.

11:09.210 --> 11:12.046
You will be supported
           as you are now.

11:20.888 --> 11:22.390
And that's all I have to say.

11:27.311 --> 11:28.396
Excuse me.

11:51.001 --> 11:54.630
I am sorry. I never thought
       it would come to this.

12:00.761 --> 12:03.347
I will require two things.

12:11.772 --> 12:14.483
Anything. My life on it.

12:17.486 --> 12:21.031
You will never have contact

12:21.073 --> 12:23.743
with Lucy Mercer ever again.

12:29.749 --> 12:31.292
And we will never...

12:32.752 --> 12:37.089
sleep in the same bed
       from this day forward.

12:41.051 --> 12:43.345
What is a marriage
       without sharing a bed?

12:46.974 --> 12:49.935
We have the rest of our lives
            to find out.

13:15.836 --> 13:17.922
Now, for the war in Afghanistan.

13:17.963 --> 13:20.341
The new US commander there
          believes that to win,

13:20.382 --> 13:22.134
he'll need a bigger Afghan army

13:22.176 --> 13:24.178
and billions
         in additional funding.

13:24.220 --> 13:26.764
An American buildup
           is already underway

13:26.806 --> 13:28.182
with 17,000 new troops...

13:28.224 --> 13:30.184
-Hey.
                -Hey.

13:30.226 --> 13:32.978
By year's end,
     US forces will total 68,000...

13:37.942 --> 13:41.070
This war's really happening.

13:41.111 --> 13:43.948
Could you imagine
   if they brought back the draft?

13:43.989 --> 13:45.574
Yeah, for sure.

13:47.201 --> 13:49.912
I also hit the Powerball today.

13:49.954 --> 13:51.956
We're millionaires now!

13:51.997 --> 13:54.333
Yeah. 
   Yeah, that's really something.

13:57.044 --> 13:58.879
Didn't hear a word I said,
              did you?

14:00.673 --> 14:02.341
My bad. You know,

14:03.217 --> 14:06.011
we spent seven hours today

14:06.053 --> 14:10.349
debating if it's important
   that poor, Black and brown kids

14:10.391 --> 14:13.018
have access
      to clean drinking water.

14:13.060 --> 14:17.189
Uh, it's fucking ridiculous.

14:17.231 --> 14:19.692
Here's a thought. How about you

14:19.733 --> 14:22.403
put politics on pause for now
       and maybe do something

14:22.444 --> 14:25.281
that doesn't make you
    such an Eeyore all the time?

14:25.322 --> 14:29.410
I'm not being
    a fucking Eeyore, all right?

14:29.451 --> 14:30.744
I care about my job--

14:30.786 --> 14:33.622
Negro, please. You're consumed.

14:33.664 --> 14:36.542
I-I can't-- 
    I can't do this again, Mich.

14:36.584 --> 14:38.586
I can't-- I'm too tired.

14:38.627 --> 14:41.797
Exactly my point. Okay? You're
    using up all your energy on--

14:41.839 --> 14:45.050
What is it you want me to do?
      You want me to resign...

14:45.092 --> 14:47.177
-Forget it.
     -...and take up some, what?

14:47.219 --> 14:49.388
Some bullshit, corporate,
        lawyer job like you?

14:49.430 --> 14:52.391
Because I'm pretty sure
          you're miserable.

14:52.433 --> 14:55.394
At least my job pays the bills.
             Our bills.

14:55.436 --> 14:57.146
We actually get
         something out of it

14:57.187 --> 14:58.898
instead of banging my head
           against a wall,

14:58.939 --> 15:00.482
telling myself that
       I'm making a difference

15:00.524 --> 15:01.734
when I'm really not.

15:05.779 --> 15:06.906
Sasha.

15:09.909 --> 15:11.076
I'll get her.

15:12.745 --> 15:14.580
I'ma sleep
     in the girls' room tonight.

15:15.581 --> 15:16.790
Fine by me.

15:30.304 --> 15:32.556
She won't stop crying.

15:32.598 --> 15:34.350
Why won't she stop crying?

15:34.391 --> 15:36.894
Oh, she's burning up.
       And her feet are cold.

15:36.936 --> 15:39.271
-I called the pediatrician.
           -We can't wait.

15:39.313 --> 15:41.941
We have to go to the hospital.
       I'm gonna call my mom.

15:41.982 --> 15:45.486
All right, go.
       Go, go, go. 

15:51.742 --> 15:53.619
Hello, I'm Michelle Obama.

15:53.661 --> 15:56.121
My pediatrician, Dr. Morrison,
         said to come here?

15:56.163 --> 15:57.581
Just a second, ma'am.

16:00.000 --> 16:02.294
-Excuse me?
    -Wait just one second, ma'am.

16:02.336 --> 16:04.338
-Mrs. Obama, follow me.
         -Thank you.

16:07.841 --> 16:09.802
What's taking them so long?

16:09.843 --> 16:11.470
The important thing

16:11.512 --> 16:14.056
is that they rule out
        bacterial meningitis.

16:14.098 --> 16:17.309
It's a spinal tap, Barack.
        On a three-month-old.

16:17.351 --> 16:19.144
I know what it is. The man--

16:19.186 --> 16:20.980
Can't they hurry up already?

16:22.856 --> 16:25.442
Mich, she's getting
     the best care in the city.

16:25.484 --> 16:28.320
Last time I was here,
         my daddy was dying.

16:39.832 --> 16:42.751
I know.
   Look, she's gonna be all right.

16:42.793 --> 16:44.044
I need a minute.

16:59.351 --> 17:00.769
Hey, Mommy.

17:13.490 --> 17:15.117
Still hasn't woken up yet?

17:23.876 --> 17:25.961
Still looking handsome, Daddy.

17:41.018 --> 17:43.562
I wish you could have seen
      him when I first met him.

17:47.066 --> 17:50.194
Juneteenth barbecue

17:51.403 --> 17:53.697
at your auntie Caroline's.

17:54.823 --> 17:57.159
In walks this

17:57.201 --> 18:00.662
beautiful, brown-skinned man

18:00.704 --> 18:04.458
in a bright teal shirt.

18:04.500 --> 18:08.003
I said, "Who is that man?"

18:08.045 --> 18:10.589
You auntie looked at me, said,

18:10.631 --> 18:14.927
"Girl, if you talkin'
      about Fraser Robinson..."

18:14.968 --> 18:18.180
"You better get in
          that long line."

18:25.062 --> 18:27.481
It was just a few seconds later,

18:27.523 --> 18:30.442
but I see your daddy
           looking at me.

18:30.484 --> 18:33.445
Hadn't even gotten a drink yet,

18:33.487 --> 18:35.531
but there he goes,

18:35.572 --> 18:39.618
making a straight beeline
           to talk to me.

18:41.787 --> 18:45.290
Well, he knew a real lady
     when he saw one. 

19:12.484 --> 19:13.986
Mr. and Mrs. Obama?

19:19.658 --> 19:22.494
-The doctor's right this way.

19:28.292 --> 19:31.879
Mr. and Mrs. Obama?
           I'm Dr. Byrne.

19:31.920 --> 19:34.131
We've done all the tests,

19:34.173 --> 19:36.466
and Sasha has
        bacterial meningitis.

19:36.508 --> 19:38.969
-We've put her on ampicillin

19:39.011 --> 19:40.762
and gentamicin, two antibiotics.

19:40.804 --> 19:42.764
We're confident
       she's going to recover.

19:42.806 --> 19:44.516
Can we go in?

19:44.558 --> 19:46.768
The nurse will let you know
      when it's okay to go in.

20:14.338 --> 20:15.547
Hi.

20:17.049 --> 20:19.092
-She'll be all right.
               -Yeah.

20:29.186 --> 20:31.188
In January 1919,

20:31.230 --> 20:33.649
two months after
          the Great War ended,

20:33.690 --> 20:36.235
delegates of the Allied Powers
            arrived in Paris

20:36.276 --> 20:39.029
for the conference to agree
            on terms of peace

20:39.071 --> 20:40.864
for defeated Germany.

20:40.906 --> 20:44.076
Sentiment across
      the board demanded guarantees

20:44.117 --> 20:48.247
that no war of such magnitude
        could ever happen again.

20:49.456 --> 20:51.375
Thank you, Arthur.
        It's good to be home.

20:51.416 --> 20:53.252
-Welcome home, sir.
           -Hello, Arthur.

20:53.293 --> 20:54.836
Welcome home, ma'am.

20:57.130 --> 20:58.632
You think the children are up?

20:58.674 --> 21:00.259
Oh, I hope not
         at this late hour.

21:00.300 --> 21:02.094
They're home,
        they're home! Daddy!

21:02.135 --> 21:06.723
-Oh, look at that. 
       -James. Anna.

21:06.765 --> 21:09.059
-We stayed up for you.
       -Tell us about France!

21:09.101 --> 21:11.311
-Did you get shot at?
      -Did you see dead bodies?

21:11.353 --> 21:14.773
No, we're fine.
       We're just a bit tired.

21:14.815 --> 21:17.276
We were not shot at,
   nor did we see any dead bodies.

21:17.317 --> 21:19.653
But we did see
     some very dramatic sights.

21:19.695 --> 21:21.196
Did Lucy go with you?

21:23.198 --> 21:25.409
No, children,
       she did not go with us.

21:25.450 --> 21:27.911
-Mother!
       -Welcome home, darling.

21:27.953 --> 21:29.788
I'm so glad you're here.

21:29.830 --> 21:31.957
Hello, Eleanor.

21:31.999 --> 21:34.376
You must be starved
      after your long journey.

21:34.418 --> 21:36.211
I-- I've made a roast for you.

21:36.253 --> 21:38.630
-Thank you.
    -If the war is over,

21:38.672 --> 21:40.924
why'd you have to go all the way
           to some country

21:40.966 --> 21:43.468
we don't even live in,
      to see where the war was?

21:43.510 --> 21:46.763
Because it's part of my job as
 Assistant Secretary to the Navy.

21:46.805 --> 21:48.932
All right, children.
       Now it's time for bed.

21:48.974 --> 21:52.477
-Come along.
       -Good night.

21:52.519 --> 21:56.982
If you don't mind,
 I'm going to head to bed myself.

21:57.024 --> 21:58.608
Oh, I hope not.

21:58.650 --> 22:01.320
I planned dinner
        for the three of us.

22:05.407 --> 22:06.700
Mmm.

22:08.410 --> 22:09.828
Delicious, Mother.

22:09.870 --> 22:11.621
I'm so glad
        you enjoyed it, dear.

22:11.663 --> 22:15.000
-You spoil me.
     -You deserve to be spoilt.

22:23.216 --> 22:27.596
Well, was it, um,
     frightfully cold in Paris?

22:27.637 --> 22:30.474
-Yes, it was very...
    -Nothing we couldn't handle.

22:31.141 --> 22:32.517
...bitter.

22:34.019 --> 22:36.688
We've all had to endure
        hard winters before.

22:36.730 --> 22:40.317
Oh, I remember
        the blizzard of '88.

22:40.359 --> 22:42.652
The snow coming down,

22:42.694 --> 22:45.447
it just made the city so quiet.

22:49.159 --> 22:52.204
Rather like this dinner,
      I should say. 

22:52.245 --> 22:54.623
-I'm sorry, Mother. 
        -I'm sorry, Mother--

22:54.664 --> 22:57.000
Just a bit tired is all.

22:57.042 --> 22:59.044
I think the trip went very well.

22:59.086 --> 23:01.671
They didn't permit
          women to attend.

23:01.713 --> 23:04.633
No, no. That was unfortunate.

23:06.385 --> 23:10.514
Did you know, that almost
     two million French soldiers

23:10.555 --> 23:12.474
were killed in the war?

23:16.269 --> 23:17.396
How dreadful.

23:17.437 --> 23:19.022
Two million.

23:20.273 --> 23:23.902
I do wish I had had the chance
         to serve. Formally.

23:23.944 --> 23:27.697
Nonsense! You did serve.
          You are serving.

23:27.739 --> 23:30.367
You have too bright
         a political future

23:30.409 --> 23:34.788
to risk losing your legs,
   have them blown off, or worse.

23:34.830 --> 23:37.040
Still, I had planned
         to return to Europe

23:37.082 --> 23:39.501
as lieutenant commander
             next month.

23:39.543 --> 23:42.337
And my political future
   would have been brighter sooner

23:42.379 --> 23:44.840
had I had the opportunity
         to serve in combat

23:44.881 --> 23:46.758
before this wretched thing
              was over.

23:46.800 --> 23:49.177
What a pity
       the war didn't drag on

23:49.219 --> 23:52.431
to give you a leg up
 in your next political endeavor.

23:52.472 --> 23:56.852
Eleanor!
   Franklin doesn't need a leg up.

23:56.893 --> 23:58.103
He's a Roosevelt.

24:03.942 --> 24:08.697
Well...
       I think I will retire.

24:08.738 --> 24:11.116
-Mother...
             -Excuse me.

24:11.158 --> 24:14.744
Thank you for taking
   such good care of the children.

24:14.786 --> 24:16.413
It's a pleasure.

24:16.455 --> 24:19.124
Good night, Eleanor.
          Good night, dear.

24:19.166 --> 24:20.625
Good night, Sara.

24:26.381 --> 24:27.799
She's right, you know?

24:33.472 --> 24:35.849
The name Roosevelt
          does open doors.

24:35.891 --> 24:37.350
Yes, it does.

24:38.143 --> 24:39.394
I am a Roosevelt.

24:41.021 --> 24:42.856
You most certainly are.

24:46.776 --> 24:48.987
I should use it.

24:49.029 --> 24:51.406
To further the causes
         that I believe in.

24:51.448 --> 24:52.741
I think you should.

24:54.034 --> 24:55.911
People have always
         taken great comfort

24:55.952 --> 24:58.955
in your strength
        and your convictions.

24:58.997 --> 25:00.499
I know I have.

25:03.210 --> 25:04.711
I know I do.

25:05.212 --> 25:06.505
Thank you.

25:08.048 --> 25:11.092
It's two 00 a.m.
          in Paris. 

25:14.221 --> 25:15.514
Good night.

25:18.058 --> 25:21.144
Good night, Eleanor.

25:34.407 --> 25:35.700
Hmm.

25:39.204 --> 25:40.580
Good night.

25:47.629 --> 25:49.923
-You cheated!

25:52.384 --> 25:55.178
-He's cheating! He's cheating!
               -Marco!

25:55.220 --> 25:57.305
-Polo!
               -Polo!

25:57.347 --> 25:59.391
-Polo!
           -Marco!

25:59.432 --> 26:01.059
-Polo!
               -Polo!

26:01.101 --> 26:03.812
-Go for him!
   -If you can cheat, I can cheat!

26:03.853 --> 26:06.815
--Marco!

26:06.856 --> 26:10.860
Polo! Your eyes are open.
          You're cheating.

26:10.902 --> 26:13.613
Boys, time for dinner.

26:14.614 --> 26:16.241
Boys!

26:18.076 --> 26:20.078
Mike? Steve, Jack.

26:20.120 --> 26:23.415
Get your butts inside now,
    or you can go to bed hungry.

26:23.456 --> 26:26.251
Clean up your messes
       and put your pets away.

26:26.293 --> 26:29.170
Steven, put that alligator
          back in its cage.

26:29.212 --> 26:31.006
After I poo!

26:31.047 --> 26:33.925
That lizard will escape
    if it has to wait that long.

26:33.967 --> 26:35.677
I'll get it, Clara.

26:35.719 --> 26:37.429
I've done it
       every night this week.

26:37.470 --> 26:40.056
I don't know why tonight
      should be any different.

26:40.098 --> 26:42.976
Lord... those teeth.

26:43.018 --> 26:46.813
Why I ever
          agreed to this...

26:46.855 --> 26:48.898
Come on, Pickles.

26:50.233 --> 26:51.568
Time for bed.

26:51.610 --> 26:54.321
-Come on. Oh, no!

26:54.362 --> 26:57.240
No, no, no! No! No! 

26:59.242 --> 27:02.621
I guess alligators don't
        like bedtime either.

27:05.790 --> 27:06.958
Steven!

27:07.667 --> 27:08.960
Jerry!

27:09.002 --> 27:10.962
Mr. Ford is still
          on his work call.

27:11.004 --> 27:12.672
Of course he is.

27:15.925 --> 27:18.219
That's right.

27:18.261 --> 27:21.473
You can't escape from me,
            you little...

27:21.514 --> 27:24.309
Oh, Clara, it's gotten so big.

27:24.351 --> 27:26.102
Let me help.

27:28.229 --> 27:32.817
Oh, don't ever have children,
      Clara. Just don't do it.

27:32.859 --> 27:35.153
I've got my hands
          full with yours.

27:40.533 --> 27:42.911
-Just please never leave me.

27:42.952 --> 27:46.164
-Oh, God!
      -I'm not going anywhere.

27:46.206 --> 27:48.083
Mom! Mommy,
    there's a fire in the house!

27:48.124 --> 27:49.626
-The cake!
              -Come on!

27:50.377 --> 27:52.128
Mommy! Mommy!

27:52.170 --> 27:54.464
Shit. Get back. Get back,
         get back, get back.

27:54.506 --> 27:57.258
Oh, we need some air in here.

27:57.300 --> 27:58.677
Jerry!

28:00.929 --> 28:02.138
Jerry!

28:02.180 --> 28:03.556
Michael, don't touch it.

28:03.598 --> 28:05.016
It's stuck!

28:05.058 --> 28:06.685
Daddy!

28:06.726 --> 28:09.270
No, Mom, it's painted shut!

28:11.481 --> 28:13.858
-Mom!

28:13.900 --> 28:16.361
Mother! Watch out, Michael.

28:17.237 --> 28:18.988
-Mommy!
         -You okay?

28:19.030 --> 28:21.032
Yeah, I'm okay,
        sweetheart. I'm okay.

28:21.074 --> 28:23.785
-Boys, help Clara.
   -Okay, I'll clean. Okay, okay.

28:23.827 --> 28:27.372
Okay, watch your step.
     Help me clean up the glass.

28:27.414 --> 28:28.790
My goodness.

28:31.042 --> 28:34.003
Ooh!

28:34.045 --> 28:38.341
How quickly
     does this work? Thank you.

28:38.383 --> 28:40.135
I have important plans,

28:40.176 --> 28:42.887
and it's such a busy time
           of year for me.

28:42.929 --> 28:46.266
Yes, my wife started spring
     cleaning herself this week.

28:46.307 --> 28:48.351
-Hmm.
      -I'm gonna also prescribe

28:48.393 --> 28:49.811
a painkiller.

28:49.853 --> 28:51.938
I can call Jerry
      and discuss it with him.

28:51.980 --> 28:54.691
-Oh, that won't be necessary.
             -Very well.

28:56.443 --> 28:59.863
You can fill
       the Darvon downstairs.

28:59.904 --> 29:01.990
Take it every four hours
          around the clock.

29:02.031 --> 29:04.617
Okay. What about alcohol?

29:05.785 --> 29:09.914
I have to attend
    so many congressional events.

29:09.956 --> 29:12.751
I occasionally enjoy
          a glass of wine.

29:12.792 --> 29:14.043
Don't worry, Mrs. Ford.

29:14.085 --> 29:15.587
Alcohol and medications

29:15.628 --> 29:17.255
are two very different things

29:17.297 --> 29:18.882
with no relation to one another.

29:18.923 --> 29:20.091
Enjoy away.

29:20.633 --> 29:22.010
Thank you, Doctor.

29:25.221 --> 29:26.973
But did you see it?

29:27.015 --> 29:28.600
Or weekends. Forget about it.

29:28.641 --> 29:30.018
I've heard that's terrible.

29:32.812 --> 29:34.397
How about we switch?

29:35.190 --> 29:36.775
I'll do the dishes.

29:38.234 --> 29:40.361
And you can go talk to them.

29:40.403 --> 29:44.783
Thank you, Ma'am.
    But I'd rather do the dishes.

29:50.038 --> 29:53.082
No. Now, look.
      That's a single crotchet

29:53.124 --> 29:55.418
but I'm pulling the needle
           through twice.

29:55.460 --> 30:00.465
I heard they're crocheting
            bikinis now.

30:00.507 --> 30:02.842
-What?
       -Oh, that's just silly.

30:05.553 --> 30:08.056
Yeah. Sounds itchy
           if you ask me.

30:08.097 --> 30:10.183
Who do you know
      wears a crotchet bikini?

30:10.225 --> 30:11.976
What about this?

30:12.018 --> 30:14.646
-Betty?

30:18.608 --> 30:22.070
Oh, surely I can't be
      the only one reading it.

30:22.111 --> 30:25.949
-I don't wanna know.

30:25.990 --> 30:27.826
-I know all about this book.
          -Do you?

30:27.867 --> 30:29.494
Yeah, this is a hysterical Jew

30:29.536 --> 30:31.621
threatening our Christian
            way of life.

30:31.663 --> 30:34.332
So, you actually read it, Lilly.

30:34.374 --> 30:37.836
No! No. I-- I didn't
            read it. I--

30:37.877 --> 30:40.797
Those feminists are--
      They're threatened by us.

30:40.839 --> 30:44.259
Yes, they are. They are. And I
    happen to like housekeeping.

30:44.300 --> 30:47.178
-I-- I find it calming.
            -That's fine.

30:47.220 --> 30:50.932
But what if
     we want to pursue creative

30:50.974 --> 30:53.810
or intellectual activities?

30:53.852 --> 30:55.812
Oh, well, who takes care
           of the children

30:55.854 --> 30:58.523
while we're all becoming
          self-actualized?

30:58.565 --> 31:00.525
I was going to be
          a dancer once...

31:00.567 --> 31:02.694
-Oh!
       -...with Martha Graham

31:02.735 --> 31:05.864
in New York,
       and sometimes I wonder

31:05.905 --> 31:10.201
what I would've become
      if I hadn't given it up.

31:10.243 --> 31:12.745
You'd be unemployed
          and way too old.

31:12.787 --> 31:15.999
--I'm sorry. It's true.

31:16.040 --> 31:18.001
That's so mean!

31:18.042 --> 31:20.753
And now you're married
      to a handsome congressman

31:20.795 --> 31:22.714
with four lovely kids
         and full-time help.

31:22.755 --> 31:24.966
Why would we want to get jobs?

31:25.008 --> 31:26.551
That would just upset
        the whole apple cart.

31:26.593 --> 31:28.052
The last thing I want

31:28.094 --> 31:29.679
is my husband washing my clothes

31:29.721 --> 31:31.639
and making me dinner.
          Can you imagine?

31:31.681 --> 31:33.892
That would be awful.

31:33.933 --> 31:36.394
It's okay, Carol.

31:36.436 --> 31:39.981
It won't bite.
       Borrow it if you like.

31:40.023 --> 31:42.400
Carol!

31:45.612 --> 31:47.822
I just wanted to see
        what she looked like.

31:47.864 --> 31:50.909
Oh, really?
    Oh, don't bother. 

31:50.950 --> 31:52.577
Take it home, Carol.

31:53.953 --> 31:56.247
She's embarrassed.

31:56.289 --> 31:58.166
No wonder she's a feminist.

32:00.293 --> 32:03.630
I want you
      to ask yourself one question.

32:03.671 --> 32:08.217
"Will I ever be great enough
   to have interesting memories?"

32:08.259 --> 32:11.429
Being a dancer may make it so,

32:11.471 --> 32:14.807
but not all of you are dancers.

32:14.849 --> 32:16.768
-Places! Let's begin!

32:34.619 --> 32:36.955
Mrs. Ford, do you need anything?

32:36.996 --> 32:39.082
No, thank you, Clara.

32:39.123 --> 32:41.084
Come sit.
    You've been working all day.

32:41.125 --> 32:44.212
-Oh, I'm not quite finished.
   -No, please. Come sit with me.

32:44.253 --> 32:46.464
I'll do the rest.

32:46.506 --> 32:49.884
-Some tea?
      -No. I'm good with this.

32:51.010 --> 32:53.179
Okay.

33:00.520 --> 33:02.063
Thank you, Clara.

33:03.022 --> 33:04.482
Do you miss it?

33:04.524 --> 33:05.650
Hmm?

33:05.692 --> 33:08.528
Your life as a dancer.

33:08.569 --> 33:11.239
Clara!

33:12.198 --> 33:14.659
Oh, that was a lifetime ago.

33:14.701 --> 33:18.204
Oh, I... mmm, loved it,

33:18.246 --> 33:22.000
the way the music
         just took me away.

33:22.041 --> 33:24.335
Living in New York City.

33:24.377 --> 33:27.422
Oh! I don't know. I--

33:27.463 --> 33:31.384
Oh, I really thought

33:31.426 --> 33:34.721
I was going to
     do something with my life.

33:34.762 --> 33:39.517
Maybe we all
         thought that once.

33:40.893 --> 33:43.855
-It's been a very long day.
              -Mm-hmm.

33:43.896 --> 33:47.191
And I can see
    that pain is acting up again.

33:47.233 --> 33:49.027
Good night, Mrs. Ford.

33:52.488 --> 33:54.866
Good night, Clara.
          Thank you again.

33:55.867 --> 33:58.369
-I'll see you tomorrow.
               -Okay.

34:54.092 --> 34:55.510
Mom just made some chicken.

34:55.551 --> 34:57.678
-Oh, really? I am starving.
              -Mm-hmm.

34:57.720 --> 34:59.388
-Huh?

34:59.430 --> 35:00.932
Hello, munchkin.

35:01.933 --> 35:03.267
Munchkin.

35:04.060 --> 35:05.353
Sweetie pie.

35:24.705 --> 35:29.377
Well, they get good hospital
   coffee. No, I mean seriously--

35:29.418 --> 35:31.337
Excuse me. Pardon me.

35:31.379 --> 35:33.840
I'm looking for a nurse
        named Judith Olstrom.

35:33.881 --> 35:36.884
She gave my baby excellent care
        here a few days ago.

35:36.926 --> 35:39.220
My husband and I just wanted
      to show our appreciation.

35:39.262 --> 35:43.182
Nothing but the best for all of
   our patients here at UChicago.

35:44.267 --> 35:46.853
I don't think that's true.

35:46.894 --> 35:49.272
We're actually one of
    the highest-ranked hospitals

35:49.313 --> 35:52.108
in the country based in
    a low-income community, so--

35:52.150 --> 35:55.778
My daughter received good care

35:55.820 --> 35:57.780
because I'm
    an Ivy-league educated lawyer

35:57.822 --> 35:59.657
with good insurance

35:59.699 --> 36:02.785
trained to navigate through
        a tangle of red tape.

36:02.827 --> 36:05.246
It's not like that
     for most folks around here.

36:05.288 --> 36:06.914
Look around.

36:06.956 --> 36:08.916
Well, I'm
      the reception will have--

36:08.958 --> 36:10.334
Folks who look just like me.

36:11.294 --> 36:12.962
I've seen it with my own eyes.

36:13.004 --> 36:15.131
I've been here under
       different circumstances

36:15.173 --> 36:18.009
with my own dad
       who was dying from MS.

36:18.050 --> 36:21.012
And still couldn't see a doctor
           for five hours.

36:25.016 --> 36:26.851
I think you can do way better.

36:26.893 --> 36:29.437
Way better? Really? 

36:29.478 --> 36:31.314
What's your name?

36:31.355 --> 36:34.108
Michelle Obama.

36:34.150 --> 36:37.403
Michelle, may I have
     five minutes of your time,

36:37.445 --> 36:39.322
please, while we're
       waiting for the nurse?

36:43.701 --> 36:46.078
-Hey, honey!

36:46.120 --> 36:49.040
There's my baby.
            Hi, munchkin.

36:54.045 --> 36:57.673
Hi, my boo-boo. 

37:00.593 --> 37:03.804
So, I have some news.

37:04.680 --> 37:06.515
-Are you pregnant?
                -No.

37:06.557 --> 37:09.227
If so, I hope it's another girl.

37:09.268 --> 37:12.313
-Please.

37:12.355 --> 37:15.149
Uh-uh. Also,
   when could that have happened?

37:15.191 --> 37:18.069
I got a job.

37:18.110 --> 37:21.072
Wha-- Oh, all right. That-- I--

37:21.113 --> 37:23.074
I didn't even
      realize you were looking.

37:23.115 --> 37:25.952
I wasn't. Uh, the job
    kind of just fell in my lap.

37:25.993 --> 37:29.455
I went to go drop off
   those flowers for nurse Judith

37:29.497 --> 37:31.999
and sort of told off the CEO

37:32.041 --> 37:33.542
and head lawyer
          for the hospital.

37:33.584 --> 37:34.877
-You what?
            -No, listen.

37:34.919 --> 37:36.587
I didn't know who they were.

37:36.629 --> 37:39.757
Anyway, they offered me a job

37:39.799 --> 37:41.926
to help them better serve
           the South Side,

37:41.968 --> 37:45.179
so, now I get to
    make a difference. 

37:45.221 --> 37:48.307
Wow. I mean, look at you.

37:48.349 --> 37:50.309
-Yes! 
             -You're...

37:50.351 --> 37:54.647
-Are you feeling all right?
      -Oh, please. Very funny.

37:54.689 --> 37:58.651
But it reminded me of why you're
    so passionate about politics.

37:58.693 --> 38:03.572
Mm-mmm, we are celebrating you.

38:03.614 --> 38:05.241
Congratulations.

38:05.283 --> 38:08.411
This is amazing.
         Whoa, look at you.

38:08.452 --> 38:10.788
Would ya look at--
          Mmm. Yeah, Mama!

38:10.830 --> 38:12.456
Mmm, you still got it.

38:12.498 --> 38:14.125
Mmm. Never lost it.

38:14.166 --> 38:16.544
-What? 
          -I never lost it.

38:18.587 --> 38:20.548
Mama got a job, munchkin.

38:20.589 --> 38:22.133
All right.

38:26.637 --> 38:29.181
Oh!

38:33.769 --> 38:37.565
-I got moves.

38:37.606 --> 38:40.234
Let's get it crunk up on

38:40.276 --> 38:44.071
Have fun up on
         Up in this dancery...

38:47.783 --> 38:49.994
-Are you out of your mind?
          -No.

38:50.036 --> 38:52.121
-Are you cooking tonight?
        -No, absolutely not.

38:52.163 --> 38:54.206
-Hello, hello, hello!
            -Ah, Barack.

38:54.248 --> 38:56.417
How you doing? Hey, babe.

38:56.459 --> 38:58.377
Now, look,
       I gotta steal her away.

38:58.419 --> 39:01.422
Oh, steal away
   but first admire her handiwork.

39:01.464 --> 39:03.174
Oh, look.
       Hey, it's a revolution!

39:03.215 --> 39:04.759
--Okay.

39:04.800 --> 39:06.761
-I'm taking you dancing.
         -Good night, guys.

39:06.802 --> 39:09.263
-You know I love this dress.
             -Thank you.

39:09.305 --> 39:10.514
Mmm. Mmm!

39:30.159 --> 39:31.452
Ladies!

39:31.494 --> 39:32.578
Ladies!

39:32.620 --> 39:34.288
Ladies! Ladies! Ladies!

39:34.330 --> 39:37.958
We have a very special
       guest lecturer tonight.

39:38.000 --> 39:40.544
She is a member of the
    Women's Trade Union League...

39:40.586 --> 39:43.005
-Aw.
   -...the League of Woman Voters.

39:44.673 --> 39:46.509
Eleanor Roosevelt.

39:53.307 --> 39:56.018
Good evening. Hello. Hello.

39:56.060 --> 40:00.314
Oh, thank you so much
       for having me to your--

40:00.356 --> 40:02.274
Sapphist salon!

40:04.235 --> 40:07.196
Well. Yes.

40:07.238 --> 40:10.199
Well, I went to a girls' school

40:10.241 --> 40:12.076
when I was younger, in England,

40:12.118 --> 40:14.829
and to this day,
          it still remains

40:14.870 --> 40:18.874
one of the happiest and
 most formative times of my life.

40:20.626 --> 40:22.753
Well,
      it is groups like yours,

40:22.795 --> 40:26.090
engaged, thinking,
          intelligent women

40:26.132 --> 40:30.428
who will assure that women's
    voices everywhere are heard.

40:34.932 --> 40:36.600
So you're gonna infiltrate

40:36.642 --> 40:38.436
the governor's mansion
          with our message.

40:40.146 --> 40:42.273
Well, I don't need to
        infiltrate anything.

40:42.314 --> 40:45.818
-I'm already there.

40:47.403 --> 40:48.946
But you know,

40:48.988 --> 40:52.450
we must not only advocate
           for our rights

40:52.491 --> 40:56.454
but the rights and safety
    of the citizens of the world.

40:56.495 --> 41:00.458
Women, children, men,
         all living beings.

41:00.499 --> 41:04.753
-Human rights. Human.
     -Yes, human rights, Esther.

41:04.795 --> 41:06.464
It's not gonna be easy

41:06.505 --> 41:09.758
when half the world is hell-bent
      on starting another war.

41:09.800 --> 41:11.510
Well, there are
         just as many people

41:11.552 --> 41:15.264
hell-bent on building
 relationships between countries.

41:15.306 --> 41:17.683
Ending isolationism,

41:17.725 --> 41:20.311
replacing it with one-world

41:20.352 --> 41:24.398
or something akin to
        a league of nations.

41:28.819 --> 41:32.114
We have had the vote now
           for nine years

41:32.156 --> 41:33.782
and there are so many women

41:33.824 --> 41:37.328
who are not exercising
             that right.

41:37.369 --> 41:40.331
Uh, worse, they are voting

41:40.372 --> 41:43.667
the way their husbands would
           have them vote.

41:43.709 --> 41:47.922
But we must encourage them
      to find their own voices

41:47.963 --> 41:51.759
and most importantly,
    to become politically active.

41:51.800 --> 41:53.344
Yes! Yes!

41:55.888 --> 41:58.891
The whole damn world
      would be much better off

41:58.933 --> 42:00.851
if the queers
        were running things.

42:02.728 --> 42:04.522
Don't mind my associate,
              Eleanor.

42:04.563 --> 42:06.690
I can't control her. 

42:06.732 --> 42:09.902
Ladies, ladies,
 we have a buffet for all of you.

42:09.944 --> 42:12.029
And um, who wants a drink?

42:19.620 --> 42:21.872
Lorena Hickok, Associated Press.

42:21.914 --> 42:25.459
Yes, I gathered. Hick.
 I've read many of your articles.

42:25.501 --> 42:27.336
-Thank you.
       -Your campaign coverage

42:27.378 --> 42:29.421
was wonderful,
         excellent in fact.

42:29.463 --> 42:31.382
You have such an original voice.

42:31.423 --> 42:34.134
Oh, you've been known
     to speak your mind as well.

42:34.176 --> 42:37.888
Yes, I've become
     quite a liability it seems.

42:37.930 --> 42:40.307
I like that in a woman.

42:42.393 --> 42:45.396
Mrs. Roosevelt, would you care
     to come have a bite to eat?

42:45.437 --> 42:48.524
Oh, uh, yes.
        Thank you very much.

42:48.566 --> 42:50.568
But you're right, you know.

42:50.609 --> 42:54.822
The fight for internationalism
   is not going to be an easy one.

42:54.863 --> 42:57.032
No, but I like friction.

42:57.074 --> 42:59.910
No conflict,
            no interest.

42:59.952 --> 43:03.080
I blame journalism

43:03.122 --> 43:05.416
and my unfortunate childhood.

43:07.084 --> 43:08.627
Well, yes.

43:09.795 --> 43:11.964
Well, it must be
        terribly interesting

43:12.006 --> 43:15.718
to write stories,
    news stories for the masses.

43:15.759 --> 43:19.096
Always something new
   and interesting to learn about.

43:19.805 --> 43:22.266
Or someone.

43:22.308 --> 43:24.143
Hick, give me a light,
             would you?

43:24.184 --> 43:25.686
Unice hid the matches
            on me again.

43:25.728 --> 43:27.062
I haven't got mine.

43:27.104 --> 43:29.356
Gail Horn,
      tell me you have matches

43:29.398 --> 43:31.317
before I go into
        tobacco withdrawals.

43:31.358 --> 43:32.943
-Come, come.
          -I don't believe

43:32.985 --> 43:35.321
I've ever seen a woman
        smoke a pipe before.

43:35.362 --> 43:37.781
Well, it's 1929.

43:38.991 --> 43:40.951
Women are doing
        all kinds of things.

43:42.995 --> 43:44.622
They certainly are.

43:48.959 --> 43:50.794
Let's see what it says.

43:50.836 --> 43:53.213
Oh, look at this bowl...

44:03.307 --> 44:05.142
What are you doing on the floor?

44:05.184 --> 44:07.770
I was thinking about the world.

44:07.811 --> 44:11.148
And I'm not on the floor,
          I'm on the stair.

44:11.190 --> 44:13.525
Thought I was having
         some strange dream.

44:13.567 --> 44:15.944
Why have you got your overcoat?
        Where are you going?

44:15.986 --> 44:18.155
I'm not going anywhere.
           I just got in.

44:18.197 --> 44:20.824
And I was taking a moment

44:20.866 --> 44:24.828
to savor
     a very stimulating evening.

44:24.870 --> 44:27.539
Hmm. Dare I ask?

44:27.581 --> 44:30.125
I was at Esther Lape
        and Elizabeth Read's

44:30.167 --> 44:32.544
women's salon on 11th Street.

44:32.586 --> 44:35.089
For God's sakes.
 All the way down in the Village?

44:35.130 --> 44:38.676
They have the most
    remarkable group of friends.

44:38.717 --> 44:41.470
Were you aware
       that women smoke pipes?

44:41.512 --> 44:42.554
I was not.

44:43.931 --> 44:47.351
As if it were the most
     natural thing in the world.

44:49.019 --> 44:53.107
They were all so singular.

44:54.233 --> 44:57.736
You know,
      it is a miraculous thing.

44:59.071 --> 45:04.118
Women have conformed
   to societal norms for so long.

45:04.159 --> 45:06.704
-I certainly have.
                -Hmm.

45:08.414 --> 45:10.958
Should we listen
      to some music, Franklin?

45:10.999 --> 45:13.377
-It's half 00.
                -Ah.

45:13.419 --> 45:16.964
Ah, it's a fine time
         for Duke Ellington.

45:22.219 --> 45:23.929
Here. 

45:23.971 --> 45:26.932
Eleanor, I admire
          your enthusiasm.

45:26.974 --> 45:29.476
It's what keeps me
         thriving and able.

45:29.518 --> 45:33.480
But your associations,
   your actions, they matter now.

45:33.522 --> 45:36.984
Yes. And I shall use them
        for the greater good.

45:37.025 --> 45:38.819
You are aware
        that you are married

45:38.861 --> 45:41.113
to the governor of
    the great state of New York?

45:41.155 --> 45:43.699
And you are the husband
             of a woman

45:43.741 --> 45:47.453
who has a mind and a life
        of her own, Franklin.

45:51.039 --> 45:55.085
I have my own interests.

45:55.127 --> 45:56.920
Just like you have yours.

45:56.962 --> 46:00.382
Thank you.

46:00.424 --> 46:03.927
Together but separate
          is how we'll be.

46:03.969 --> 46:05.637
It's how we already are.

46:07.890 --> 46:11.101
I have no intention
         of embarrassing you

46:11.143 --> 46:13.771
and I hope
       you won't embarrass me.

46:14.396 --> 46:15.439
Right.

46:17.232 --> 46:18.275
Cheers.

46:26.033 --> 46:27.576
Good night, Eleanor.

46:31.872 --> 46:33.791
You look lovely.

46:37.878 --> 46:39.421
-Hi, Dad.
        -Hey, champ.

46:39.463 --> 46:40.964
Did you guys
         win the game this week?

46:41.006 --> 46:42.841
I didn't score but we won.

46:42.883 --> 46:45.761
As long as you play,
 you're part of the winning team.

46:45.803 --> 46:47.221
Where are you, Dad?

46:47.262 --> 46:49.431
Midland, Michigan, Steven.

46:49.473 --> 46:51.099
Home of
      the Dow Chemical Company.

46:51.141 --> 46:52.184
Okay.

46:53.936 --> 46:55.896
Brown Sugar's pregnant, Dad.

46:55.938 --> 46:59.149
Now hold on.
      Isn't Brown Sugar a boy?

46:59.191 --> 47:02.236
I don't know.
     Mom, is Brown Sugar a boy?

47:02.986 --> 47:03.862
No.

47:05.531 --> 47:08.116
-Hi, Daddy.
      -How's my little girl doing?

47:08.158 --> 47:10.285
Fine. Me and Clara made fudge.

47:10.327 --> 47:13.747
Oh, boy. I love you, sweetie.

47:13.789 --> 47:15.415
It's me, Jerry.

47:15.457 --> 47:18.919
Well, I love you too, sweetie.

47:18.961 --> 47:20.337
See you Saturday.

47:20.379 --> 47:22.172
All right, bye-bye.

47:34.893 --> 47:36.228
You and the family

47:36.270 --> 47:38.021
get out to Vail
          for the holidays?

47:39.690 --> 47:41.525
No, we skipped it this year.

47:42.442 --> 47:44.862
Jerry had to work, so...

47:44.903 --> 47:46.697
Well, your range of motion
           hasn't improved

47:46.738 --> 47:49.032
as much as I hoped it would
      over the last few months.

47:49.074 --> 47:52.327
The only time I'm not in pain
         is when I'm asleep.

47:53.453 --> 47:56.081
-If I sleep.
 -How long's sleep been an issue?

47:57.875 --> 48:00.544
Since I got married
          and had children.

48:05.257 --> 48:07.551
Do you have children,
            Dr. McCarten?

48:08.260 --> 48:10.637
I, um-- Let's do this.

48:11.763 --> 48:14.266
Let's get you
      some mild sleeping pills.

48:16.894 --> 48:20.647
And I think I'd like to
    up the Darvon a notch or two,

48:20.689 --> 48:23.317
so we can get
       that pain knocked out.

48:24.860 --> 48:26.028
And finally...

48:28.363 --> 48:29.907
a small amount of Valium

48:29.948 --> 48:31.992
should help
    with your day-to-day stress.

48:38.999 --> 48:41.877
Um, say hi to Jerry for me.

48:51.720 --> 48:53.055
Clara!

48:57.893 --> 48:58.936
Clara?

49:22.834 --> 49:24.503
Oh, goddamn it.

49:25.462 --> 49:28.590
Clara! Clara!

50:19.391 --> 50:20.684
Nice.

50:23.353 --> 50:24.396
Very nice.

50:25.981 --> 50:29.985
Most of you
      have a lot of work to do.

50:30.027 --> 50:31.611
That's enough for today.

50:36.575 --> 50:39.369
You impressed me today,
           Betty Bloomer.

50:39.411 --> 50:42.956
You work hard
        and you have ability.

50:42.998 --> 50:45.834
The trouble is
     everyone here has ability.

50:45.876 --> 50:49.046
A dancer needs confidence,
            self-esteem.

50:50.088 --> 50:51.715
Do you have those?

50:53.258 --> 50:54.718
Mmm.

51:40.305 --> 51:41.598
Cheers.

51:54.152 --> 51:59.074
Stop! Why would a dancer treat
     her body with such disdain?

51:59.116 --> 52:01.284
You will do it again.
           And then again.

52:01.326 --> 52:03.245
And again. And again.

52:12.462 --> 52:14.297
Uh.

52:14.339 --> 52:16.550
Mom, I'm hungry.

52:18.510 --> 52:20.554
Is Clara here?
       Can I have a sandwich?

52:21.638 --> 52:24.141
-Close the door.
           -I know.

52:24.182 --> 52:26.351
-Are you sleeping?

52:28.103 --> 52:32.899
No. No, honey. I'm just--
       just resting. 

52:35.485 --> 52:37.571
Mom, I've got
   some friends coming over later.

52:37.612 --> 52:39.406
No, Michael. Not today.

52:39.447 --> 52:41.992
But you said yes earlier.
    I already invited them over.

52:43.660 --> 52:45.662
Hey! These are mine.

52:48.123 --> 52:50.083
Do you want to play
     Barrel of Monkeys with me?

52:50.125 --> 52:51.501
No, sweetie. Not now.

53:07.267 --> 53:10.478
Steven, turn the music down.

53:34.211 --> 53:37.964
S-- Steven!

53:40.008 --> 53:43.386
Steven! Open the door!

53:43.428 --> 53:45.555
-Open the door!

53:45.597 --> 53:49.559
--Steven!

54:09.454 --> 54:10.747
Mommy?

54:11.790 --> 54:14.417
Go-- Go--
     Go pack your things, Susan.

54:16.253 --> 54:17.420
Go on.

54:40.610 --> 54:43.321
Susan! Susan!

54:46.783 --> 54:48.618
Come on. Let's go, Susan.

54:50.495 --> 54:52.038
Come on. Let's go.

54:53.832 --> 54:55.292
Come on. 

54:57.294 --> 54:59.921
Mom. Mom, what's happening?

54:59.963 --> 55:02.173
I'm taking Susan to the beach.

55:03.008 --> 55:04.718
Are you sure that's a good idea?

55:06.344 --> 55:09.055
-Mom, what's going on?
   -What if we just wait

55:09.097 --> 55:11.599
-till Dad comes home?
 -Mom, what's wrong? Mom?

55:11.641 --> 55:13.727
Wait for Dad to get home!

55:13.768 --> 55:15.478
-Mom. Mom.
     -It'll be okay. I promise.

55:16.604 --> 55:19.149
-If this is about the music...
            -Oh, please.

55:19.190 --> 55:22.152
...we can turn it down.
       We'll clean the house.

55:22.193 --> 55:23.695
We can do whatever you like.

55:24.404 --> 55:26.614
Mom, please don't do this.

55:26.656 --> 55:29.659
-Mom, please don't do this.
    -Michael, let go of the door!

55:32.203 --> 55:34.539
Where are the keys?
       Did you take the keys?

55:34.581 --> 55:37.083
Michael, did you take them?

55:37.125 --> 55:39.377
Did you take them?
       Where did you put them?

55:40.420 --> 55:43.423
What is-- Clara.
         Did you call Clara?

55:43.465 --> 55:46.134
-Mrs. Ford.
          -What did you do?

55:46.176 --> 55:47.761
I'm here, Mrs. Ford.

55:47.802 --> 55:50.138
I came right back
      as soon as you needed me.

55:50.180 --> 55:51.931
Are you okay, Mrs. Ford?

55:51.973 --> 55:56.102
I don't--
         I don't-- I don't--

55:57.812 --> 56:01.024
Mrs. Ford, I'm here.

56:01.066 --> 56:04.694
Oh, my-- What did you do?
          What did you do?

56:09.074 --> 56:10.617
Clara, I'll take care of it.

56:10.658 --> 56:12.369
-Betty.
                -Mom.

56:12.410 --> 56:14.871
Michael, take care
     of your brother and sister.

56:18.416 --> 56:21.461
Children, come here.
        I know you're scared.

56:22.545 --> 56:25.840
Your mom loves you all
             very much.

56:25.882 --> 56:29.677
And, uh, she's just
          very, very tired.

56:29.719 --> 56:32.597
She's gonna get help
            from a doctor

56:32.639 --> 56:34.557
and he's gonna
        help her get better.

56:36.184 --> 56:37.560
You okay, Michael?

56:39.938 --> 56:41.356
You did good.

56:57.122 --> 56:58.289
Jerry.

57:04.587 --> 57:08.341
Please tell the children
           that I'm sorry.

57:10.385 --> 57:13.930
I will, Mother.
        You sleep now, okay?

57:19.978 --> 57:21.104
I love you.

57:29.904 --> 57:32.240
You've all auditioned very well

57:32.282 --> 57:35.076
and I'm appreciative
          of your efforts.

57:35.118 --> 57:38.246
I'm sorry to say,
       none of you are great,

57:38.288 --> 57:40.832
but some of you do show promise.

57:40.874 --> 57:43.585
Meg, you're in.

57:44.502 --> 57:46.504
Elizabeth, you're in.

57:46.546 --> 57:47.964
Callie, you're cut.

57:48.006 --> 57:49.883
Helen, in.

57:49.924 --> 57:52.594
Betty, you're out.

57:54.220 --> 57:55.763
If you can care for yourself,

57:55.805 --> 57:57.807
maybe you can come back
           and try again.

57:57.849 --> 58:01.686
Trudy, you're in.
     Jennifer, in. Natalie, in.
